'''David Berkman''' (born December 28, 1958) is an American [[jazz]] pianist, composer, arranger and educator.

==Background==
Berkman grew up in Cleveland, Ohio, playing in house bands for visiting jazz musicians [[Sonny Stitt]], [[Hank Crawford]], and [[Carter Jefferson]] and locals [[Joe Lovano]], [[Jamey Haddad]], and [[Greg Bandy]]. He moved to New York City in 1985.

As a composer, Berkman was awarded the 2000 Doris Duke/Chamber Music America New Works Creation and Presentation Grant.<ref>{{cite web|title=Past Recipients|url=http://www.chamber-music.org/programs/recipients.html#encore |accessdate=June 21, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418120207/http://www.chamber-music.org/programs/recipients.html |archivedate=April 18, 2009 }}</ref> He is a recording artist whose four Palmetto recordings have appeared on numerous best records of the year critics' lists: ''[[The New York Times]]'' (Top 10 Records of 1998), the ''[[Village Voice]]'' (Top 10 Records of 1998), ''[[Down Beat]]'' (Best records of the 90s), ''JazzIz'' (Top 5 records of 1998), ''Jazz Times'' and others. Critic John Stevenson wrote in his 2000 review of Berkman's ''Leaving Home'', "With Leaving Home, (Berkman) has ascended to a new height of creativity. Tracing the trajectory of mapped out by his earlier CD's we can see a greater level of melodic sophistication and more intense coalescing of compositional elements".<ref>John Stevenson, CD Reviews.com "Best CDs of 2000 --Jim Macnie, SonicNet, Providence Register</ref> As a jazz clinician, Berkman was awarded the Homer Osborne Award from the Wichita Jazz Society and has performed and taught at numerous jazz camps, universities and conservatories around the United States, South America and Europe.

Berkman published three books with Sher Music Publishing: ''The Jazz Musician's Guide to Creative Practicing'' (2007), ''The Jazz Singer's Guidebook'' (2009) and ''The Jazz Harmony Book'' (2014).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.shermusic.com |title = Jazz & Latin Music Real Books and Method Books | publisher = Sher Music Co }}</ref> He has played in many bands including, most importantly, says [[Scott Yanow]] of the ''[[All Music Guide to Jazz]]''<ref>{{Allmusic | class = artist | id = p148039 | tab = biography | label = Biography of David Berkman |first = Scott | last = Yanow | accessdate = 2012-05-08 }}</ref> those of [[Cecil McBee]], whose 2003 CD ''Unspoken'' includes Berkman.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.palmetto-records.com/album.php?album=97 | title = Unspoken | publisher = [[Palmetto Records]] | accessdate = 2012-05-08 }}</ref> Berkman has performed with Tom Harrell and the Vanguard Orchestra and has performed with, recorded or arranged for numerous jazz musicians, including Sonny Stitt, [[Brian Blade]], Joe Lovano, [[Dave Douglas (trumpeter)|Dave Douglas]], [[Ray Drummond]], [[Billy Hart]], [[Dick Oatts]], [[Tony Malaby]], [[Chris Potter (jazz saxophonist)|Chris Potter]], [[Scott Wendholt]], [[Lenny White]], [[Scott Colley]], [[Craig Handy]], [[Steven Bernstein (musician)|Steven Bernstein]], [[Bill Stewart (musician)|Bill Stewart]], [[Dave Stryker]], [[David "Fathead" Newman]], Hank Crawford, and [[Jane Monheit]] )<ref>{{Allmusic | class = artist | id = p148039 | tab = credits | label = Credits for David Berkman | accessdate = 2012-05-08 }}</ref>

Now appearing more often as a bandleader, Berkman has performed solo and with his quartet, quintet and sextet at festivals and clubs in the United States, Europe and Japan, most recently at the [[North Sea Jazz Festival]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.northseajazz.com/en/history/2004.aspx?date=20040711 | title = Timetable for Sunday 11 July 2004 |publisher= [[North Sea Jazz]]}}</ref> the [[Edinburgh Festival]],<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://content.yudu.com/Library/A15srv/ThreeWeeksinEdinburg/resources/22.htm | journal = ThreeWeeks in Edinburgh | title = Week Zero: Preview Edition | page = 22 | year = 2008 }}</ref> the [[Glasgow Jazz Festival]], the [[Belfast Festival at Queen's|Belfast Festival]] and the [[Cork Festival]]. Recent tours include clubs and concert performances in Germany, Switzerland, Ireland, the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, Austria, Belgium, SÃ£o Paulo, Japan and around the United States. Recent projects include piano/trumpet duo performances with Dave Douglas, at the 2006 Jazz Composers Symposium in Tampa, Florida, and the 2005 International Trumpet Guild Convention in [[Bangkok]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.trumpetguild.org/2005conference/wed/212.html | title = ITG 2005<!-- Bot generated title --> }}</ref> and with [[Tom Harrell]] in Italy, as well as the cooperatively-led New York Standards Quartet (with Tim Armacost, Yosuke Inoue, and Gene Jackson).<ref>{{official website|1=http://nysq.org|2=New York Standards Quartet}}</ref> ''Old Friends and New Friends'' on Palmetto Records was released May 5, 2015 and features Brian Blade on drums, Linda May Han Oh on bass, and Dayna Stephens, Adam Kolker, and Billy Drewes on saxophones.

Berkman is an associate professor and Director of Jazz Studies at the [[Queens College, City University of New York|Queens College]] in New York City and is a visiting professor at the [[Prince Claus Conservatoire]] in [[Groningen]], the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hanze.nl/home/International/Schools/Prins+Claus+Conservatorium/Programmes/Bachelor+Programmes/Jazz | title = New York comes to Groningen | publisher = [[Hanze University of Applied Sciences, Groningen]]<!-- Bot generated title --> }}</ref>

